In C, you can declare multiple variables of the **same data type** in a single statement, which can enhance code readability and reduce redundancy. This is especially useful when you need to work with multiple variables of the same type.

**Syntax:**

```c
data_type var1, var2, var3;  // Syntax 1: Multiple variables declared without initial values
data_type var1 = value1, var2 = value2, var3 = value3;  // Syntax 2: Multiple variables initialized with values
```

---

**Example:**

```c
#include

int main() {
    // Syntax 1: Declare multiple variables without initialization and assign values later
    int age, height, weight;
    age = 25; height = 175; weight = 68;

    // Syntax 2: Declare and initialize multiple variables in one statement
    int length = 10, width = 20, area = 200;

    // Output the values of all variables
    printf("Age: %d, Height: %d, Weight: %d\n", age, height, weight);
    printf("Length: %d, Width: %d, Area: %d", length, width, area);

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output:**

```default
Age: 25, Height: 175, Weight: 68
Length: 10, Width: 20, Area: 200
```

